        "text": "Managing high blood pressure, or hypertension, involves a combination of lifestyle changes and, if necessary, medication. Here are some best practices based on recent guidelines and research:\n\n1. **Lifestyle Modifications**: Adopting a heart-healthy lifestyle can effectively manage high blood pressure and reduce the risk of associated health conditions. Key strategies include maintaining a balanced diet low in salt and rich in fruits and vegetables, exercising regularly, and managing stress levels. Aerobic exercises such as walking, running, cycling, swimming, and even high-intensity interval training (HIIT) are particularly beneficial in lowering blood pressure [heart.org](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure) [mayoclinic.org](https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974).\n\n2. **Regular Monitoring**: Accurate measurement of blood pressure is crucial for the diagnosis and management of hypertension. This includes conventional office blood pressure measurement and, in some cases, home or ambulatory blood pressure monitoring [portailvasculaire.fr](https://www.portailvasculaire.fr/sites/default/files/docs/2024_esh_hta.pdf).\n\n3. **Medication Adherence**: When prescribed, antihypertensive medications must be taken consistently as directed by healthcare providers. These medications can improve quality of life and ward off complications related to untreated high blood pressure [pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37712135/).\n\n4. **Consulting Guidelines**: It's vital to stay informed about and adhere to the guidelines set forth by esteemed bodies like the American Heart Association and European Society of Hypertension, which reflect the latest research and expert consensus on managing high blood pressure [portailvasculaire.fr](https://portailvasculaire.fr/sites/default/files/docs/2025_aha_guide_bp_hta.pdf).\n\n5. **Education and Support**: Engaging in patient education and support programs where available can help individuals better understand their condition and the importance of adherence to treatment plans [pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37712135/).\n\nTogether, these practices can significantly reduce the risk of cardiovascular diseases associated with hypertension.\n\n# CITATIONS\n\n1. [How to Manage High Blood Pressure | American Heart Association](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure)\n\n- There are actions you can take to control your blood pressure. - Adopting a heart-healthy lifestyle can reduce your blood pressure and lower your risk for other conditions. High blood pressure, also known as hypertension, is often called a “silent killer” because it usually has no symptoms. It can affect all age groups: children, young adults, adults and older adults. High blood pressure quietly damages blood vessels and leads to serious health problems. There is no cure. But using medications as prescribed and making lifestyle changes can improve your quality of life and control your blood pressure.\n\n2. [2025 AHA/ACC/AANP/AAPA/ABC/ACCP/ACPM/AGS/AMA/ASPC/NMA/PCNA/SGIM Guideline for the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation and Management of High Blood Pressure in Adults: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines](https://portailvasculaire.fr/sites/default/files/docs/2025_aha_guide_bp_hta.pdf)\n\n‖‖American Society of Preventive Cardiology (ASPC) Representative. ¶¶American Geriatrics Society (AGS) Representative. Peer Review Committee Members and ACC/AHA Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines Members, see page __. The American Heart Association requests that this document be cited as follows: 2025 AHA/ACC/AANP/AAPA/ABC/ACCP/ACPM/AGS/AMA/ASPC/NMA/ PCNA/SGIM Guideline for the prevention, detection, evaluation, and management of high blood pressure in adults: a report of the American College of Cardiology/ American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines.\n\n3. [Lifestyle management of hypertension: International Society of Hypertension position paper endorsed by the World Hypertension League and European Society of Hypertension - PubMed](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37712135/)\n\nThe first SundayThe first MondayThe first TuesdayThe first WednesdayThe first ThursdayThe first FridayThe first SaturdayThe first dayThe first weekday Hypertension, defined as persistently elevated systolic blood pressure (SBP) >140 mmHg and/or diastolic blood pressure (DBP) at least 90 mmHg (International Society of Hypertension guidelines), affects over 1.5 billion people worldwide. Hypertension is associated with increased risk of cardiovascular disease (CVD) events (e.g. coronary heart disease, heart failure and stroke) and death. An international panel of experts convened by the International Society of Hypertension College of Experts compiled lifestyle management recommendations as first-line strategy to prevent and control hypertension in adulthood.\n\n4. [2024 European Society of Hypertension clinical practice guidelines for the management of arterial hypertension](https://www.portailvasculaire.fr/sites/default/files/docs/2024_esh_hta.pdf)\n\nThe accurate measurement of blood pressure (BP) is the cornerstone for the diagnosis and management of hypertension. The measurement of BP to diagnose hypertension therefore represents the first pivotal step of the ESH MASTERplan for the management of hypertension. • Conventional attended office BP measurement (OBPM) is the most well-studied method for assessing BP and the one by which the diagnosis of hypertension, BP classification, the role of BP as a car diovascular (CV) risk factor, the protective effect of antihypertensive treatment and the BP thresholds and targets of therapeutic in • Ambulatory BP monitoring (ABPM) and home BP monitoring\n\n5. [10 ways to control high blood pressure without medication](https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974)\n\nIt's important to keep exercising to keep blood pressure from rising again. As a general goal, aim for at least 30 minutes of moderate physical activity every day. Exercise also can help keep elevated blood pressure that's slightly higher than ideal from turning into high blood pressure, also called hypertension. For those who have hypertension, regular physical activity can bring blood pressure down to safer levels. Some examples of aerobic exercise that can help lower blood pressure include walking, jogging, cycling, swimming and dancing. Another helpful type of exercise is high-intensity interval training.\n",
