        "text": "Experts recommend managing **high blood pressure (hypertension)** primarily through lifestyle changes and, when necessary, medication guided by risk assessment tools like the PREVENT risk calculator. Core lifestyle recommendations include staying physically active, following a heart-healthy diet (like the DASH diet), reducing sodium intake, increasing potassium intake, limiting alcohol consumption, maintaining a healthy weight, and managing stress[[2]](https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756)[[3]](https://newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk)[[6]](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure)[[8]](https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/high-blood-pressure/treatment)[[10]](https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974).\n\nKey expert guidance from updated 2025 guidelines emphasizes:\n\n- **Physical activity** as a fundamental approach to lower blood pressure[[6]](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure).\n- **Dietary changes** such as adopting the DASH diet, which is rich in fruits, vegetables (high in potassium), whole grains, and low in saturated fats and sodium, shown to significantly reduce blood pressure[[2]](https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756)[[6]](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure)[[8]](https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/high-blood-pressure/treatment)[[10]](https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974)[[15]](https://www.nm.org/healthbeat/healthy-tips/what-can-i-do-to-lower-my-blood-pressure).\n- **Weight loss** if overweight or obese to help reduce blood pressure[[2]](https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756).\n- **Limiting alcohol intake** (no more than two drinks/day for men, one for women)[[2]](https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756).\n- **Medication** is recommended based on individual 10-year cardiovascular risk, as calculated by tools like PREVENT, especially for stage 1 hypertension patients with cardiovascular disease or higher risk[[1]](https://professional.heart.org/en/science-news/2025-high-blood-pressure-guideline)[[5]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12425457/)[[9]](https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jacc.2025.07.010)[[11]](https://www.ama-assn.org/public-health/prevention-wellness/new-bp-guideline-5-things-physicians-should-know).\n- **Starting treatment with two medications simultaneously**, ideally single-pill combinations, for many patients to improve adherence and effectiveness[[7]](https://www.acc.org/Latest-in-Cardiology/Journal-Scans/2025/08/14/15/36/New-ACC-AHA-Guideline-Addresses-Prevention-Detection-Evaluation-and-Management-of-HBP).\n- Newer therapies like GLP-1 receptor agonists may be considered for patients with hypertension plus obesity or overweight[[3]](https://newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk)[[7]](https://www.acc.org/Latest-in-Cardiology/Journal-Scans/2025/08/14/15/36/New-ACC-AHA-Guideline-Addresses-Prevention-Detection-Evaluation-and-Management-of-HBP).\n- Emphasis on **home blood pressure monitoring** and **team-based care** to improve blood pressure control[[1]](https://professional.heart.org/en/science-news/2025-high-blood-pressure-guideline)[[3]](https://newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk).\n\nAdditional expert advice includes consideration of supplements such as potassium, magnesium, omega-3 fatty acids, and hibiscus tea, but only after consulting a healthcare professional to avoid interactions with medications[[4]](https://www.goodrx.com/conditions/hypertension/best-high-blood-pressure-supplements).\n\nIn summary, experts recommend a **comprehensive approach** combining lifestyle modifications first and adding medications guided by cardiovascular risk assessments for optimal control of hypertension and reduction of associated cardiovascular and other complications[[1]](https://professional.heart.org/en/science-news/2025-high-blood-pressure-guideline)[[3]](https://newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk)[[5]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12425457/)[[7]](https://www.acc.org/Latest-in-Cardiology/Journal-Scans/2025/08/14/15/36/New-ACC-AHA-Guideline-Addresses-Prevention-Detection-Evaluation-and-Management-of-HBP)[[8]](https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/high-blood-pressure/treatment).\n\n# CITATIONS\n\n1. [professional.heart.org/en/science-news/2025-high-blood-pressure-guideline](https://professional.heart.org/en/science-news/2025-high-blood-pressure-guideline)\n\n2. [www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756](https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/new-high-blood-pressure-guidelines-2017111712756)\n\n3. [newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk](https://newsroom.heart.org/news/new-high-blood-pressure-guideline-emphasizes-prevention-early-treatment-to-reduce-cvd-risk)\n\n4. [www.goodrx.com/conditions/hypertension/best-high-blood-pressure-supplements](https://www.goodrx.com/conditions/hypertension/best-high-blood-pressure-supplements)\n\n5. [pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12425457/](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12425457/)\n\n6. [www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure)\n\n7. [www.acc.org/Latest-in-Cardiology/Journal-Scans/2025/08/14/15/36/New-ACC-AHA-Guideline-Addresses-Prevention-Detection-Evaluation-and-Management-of-HBP](https://www.acc.org/Latest-in-Cardiology/Journal-Scans/2025/08/14/15/36/New-ACC-AHA-Guideline-Addresses-Prevention-Detection-Evaluation-and-Management-of-HBP)\n\n8. [www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/high-blood-pressure/treatment](https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/high-blood-pressure/treatment)\n\n9. [www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jacc.2025.07.010](https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jacc.2025.07.010)\n\n10. [www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974](https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/high-blood-pressure/in-depth/high-blood-pressure/art-20046974)\n\n11. [www.ama-assn.org/public-health/prevention-wellness/new-bp-guideline-5-things-physicians-should-know](https://www.ama-assn.org/public-health/prevention-wellness/new-bp-guideline-5-things-physicians-should-know)\n\n12. [my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/4314-hypertension-high-blood-pressure](https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/4314-hypertension-high-blood-pressure)\n\n13. [www.jwatch.org/na59168/2025/09/25/comprehensive-and-updated-hypertension-guideline](https://www.jwatch.org/na59168/2025/09/25/comprehensive-and-updated-hypertension-guideline)\n\n14. [www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure/types-of-blood-pressure-medications](https://www.heart.org/en/health-topics/high-blood-pressure/changes-you-can-make-to-manage-high-blood-pressure/types-of-blood-pressure-medications)\n\n15. [www.nm.org/healthbeat/healthy-tips/what-can-i-do-to-lower-my-blood-pressure](https://www.nm.org/healthbeat/healthy-tips/what-can-i-do-to-lower-my-blood-pressure)\n",
